But this guy was   so   talented.

396
00:18:54.133 --> 00:18:56.343
So he invited me
        to this thing called

397
00:18:56.343 --> 00:18:57.678
the Tuesday Night Music Club.

398
00:18:57.678 --> 00:19:01.890
-What in the world is
   the Tuesday Night Music Club?

399
00:19:01.890 --> 00:19:03.851
-A club of wild partiers

400
00:19:03.851 --> 00:19:06.687
who all happen to be
           artists in L.A.

401
00:19:06.687 --> 00:19:08.105
It was a pretty heady crowd.

402
00:19:08.105 --> 00:19:09.648
I mean. it was
          a lot of drinking

403
00:19:09.648 --> 00:19:11.608
and some guys dropping acid.

404
00:19:11.608 --> 00:19:14.695
I mean. it was like
            freethinkers.

405
00:19:14.695 --> 00:19:17.197
-Kevin Gilbert brought her in

406
00:19:17.197 --> 00:19:21.368
to our Tuesday Night session
           very early on.

407
00:19:21.368 --> 00:19:22.828
It was unbelievable.

408
00:19:22.828 --> 00:19:27.541
Something of a higher order
           came together.

409
00:19:28.333 --> 00:19:31.211
-I think the first session
               we did.

410
00:19:31.211 --> 00:19:34.298
we wrote and recorded
        "Leaving Las Vegas."

411
00:19:34.298 --> 00:19:36.383
-Sheryl took the lyric sheet
        and started singing.

412
00:19:36.383 --> 00:19:40.596
She sat over on a chair over
     in the corner and sang it.

413
00:19:40.596 --> 00:19:41.972
and she sang
         the shit out of it.

414
00:19:41.972 --> 00:19:46.226
-I remember Bill saying to me.
        "I love your singing

415
00:19:46.226 --> 00:19:49.062
when you're not trying
           to sing great."

416
00:19:49.062 --> 00:19:52.524
-The diversity of her vocals.
     I mean. it's unbelievable.

417
00:19:52.524 --> 00:19:55.569
She owns every song.
        owns every character.

418
00:19:55.569 --> 00:20:00.282
When she sings
       and also when we write.

419
00:20:00.282 --> 00:20:01.575
everything came to life.

420
00:20:01.575 --> 00:20:04.536
-I think up until that point.
       there was not. like. a.

421
00:20:04.536 --> 00:20:06.663
"We're making
      a record   for   this girl."

422
00:20:06.663 --> 00:20:10.751
And then Bill started really
       managing the situation.

423
00:20:10.751 --> 00:20:12.878
only letting people come in
            when needed.

424
00:20:12.878 --> 00:20:15.756
And Kevin didn't like
         not being invited.

425
00:20:15.756 --> 00:20:18.258
so that started
       to cause real friction.

426
00:20:18.258 --> 00:20:21.220
and our relationship
       started deteriorating.

427
00:20:21.220 --> 00:20:25.182
-I was in charge of
           getting it made

428
00:20:25.182 --> 00:20:28.060
and curating it.
         if that's the word.

429
00:20:28.060 --> 00:20:29.394
It's like a stew.

430
00:20:29.394 --> 00:20:34.274
The other band guys --
    they weren't there for that.

431
00:20:34.274 --> 00:20:35.692
-We would drink a bunch.

432
00:20:35.692 --> 00:20:37.778
we'd go to the bookstore
           down the road.

433
00:20:37.778 --> 00:20:41.406
and we bought a poetry book
   by this man named Wyn Cooper.

434
00:20:41.406 --> 00:20:44.701
And there was a poem in it
      first thing called "Fun."

435
00:20:44.701 --> 00:20:46.245
It started off with.
          "All I want to do

436
00:20:46.245 --> 00:20:49.331
is have a little fun
           before I die."

437
00:20:49.331 --> 00:20:51.458
And so we had
          this groove going

438
00:20:51.458 --> 00:20:54.294
that was somewhere between
           Stealers Wheel

439
00:20:54.294 --> 00:20:56.380
and a Marvin Gaye track.

440
00:20:56.380 --> 00:20:57.714
and I picked up
           the poetry book

441
00:20:57.714 --> 00:21:00.634
and started just
         kind of free form.

442
00:21:00.634 --> 00:21:03.470
All I wanna do is have
     a little fun before I die

443
00:21:03.470 --> 00:21:05.973
Says a man next to me
          out of nowhere

444
00:21:05.973 --> 00:21:08.850
And I just kind of
         acted out the poem.

445
00:21:08.850 --> 00:21:12.604
And then we put
           this hook in --

446
00:21:12.604 --> 00:21:14.690
All I wanna do

447
00:21:14.690 --> 00:21:15.816
And that became the song.

448
00:21:15.816 --> 00:21:18.860
All I wanna do
         is have some fun

449
00:21:18.860 --> 00:21:22.739
I got a feeling
       I'm not the only one

450
00:21:22.739 --> 00:21:24.032
Well. all I wanna do

451
00:21:24.032 --> 00:21:26.618
By the end of the record.
      I was thinking. you know.

452
00:21:26.618 --> 00:21:29.788
that song is really cool.
 but it's -- it's such a B-side

453
00:21:29.788 --> 00:21:33.792
and it's so esoteric
           and so quirky.

454
00:21:33.792 --> 00:21:35.502
We should just leave it off.

455
00:21:35.502 --> 00:21:36.878
And Bill's like.
      "We   can't   leave it off."

456
00:21:36.878 --> 00:21:38.588
And I was like. "Well.
      I got to contact this guy

457
00:21:38.588 --> 00:21:41.466
and tell him
        we've used his poem."

458
00:21:41.466 --> 00:21:43.468
So we looked for him.
            I called him.

459
00:21:43.468 --> 00:21:45.387
I was like.
     "I know you don't know me.

460
00:21:45.387 --> 00:21:46.805
We've used your poem.

461
00:21:46.805 --> 00:21:49.683
We want to give you. you know.
        half the songwriting.

462
00:21:49.683 --> 00:21:52.144
should the thing
     ever see the light of day."

463
00:21:52.144 --> 00:21:55.272
And he's like. "Oh.
     that's great. that's great.

464
00:21:57.149 --> 00:22:00.569
I like a good beer buzz
       early in the morning

465
00:22:00.569 --> 00:22:02.571
And Billy likes to
          peel the labels

466
00:22:02.571 --> 00:22:03.947
Off those bottles of Bud

467
00:22:03.947 --> 00:22:08.076
The anniversary Woodstock
     in '94 was a game changer.

468
00:22:08.076 --> 00:22:10.704
We came out
   and we played our hearts out.

469
00:22:10.704 --> 00:22:14.458
and then suddenly
       we were being noticed.

470
00:22:14.458 --> 00:22:17.127
-It's really quite a thing
             to witness.

471
00:22:17.127 --> 00:22:18.754
It's like a match striking

472
00:22:18.754 --> 00:22:21.506
and then somebody
         throwing oil on it.

473
00:22:21.506 --> 00:22:23.508
It moves so fast
         you don't even know

474
00:22:23.508 --> 00:22:25.260
what your next move is.

475
00:22:25.260 --> 00:22:31.016
- Until the sun comes up
   over Santa Monica Boulevard

476
00:22:31.016 --> 00:22:33.018
-All of a sudden
      you're hearing it. like.

477
00:22:33.018 --> 00:22:36.021
in drugstores
         and grocery stores

478
00:22:36.021 --> 00:22:39.649
and then magazines
        are talking about it.

479
00:22:39.649 --> 00:22:43.737
Hairdressers are giving people
       the Sheryl Crow curls.

480
00:22:43.737 --> 00:22:45.447
The song was everywhere.

481
00:22:45.447 --> 00:22:50.243
- All I wanna do
         is have some fun

482
00:22:50.243 --> 00:22:51.578
-Oh!

483
00:22:51.578 --> 00:22:53.497
-There's a moment
           when a hit song

484
00:22:53.497 --> 00:22:55.499
takes on its own life.

485
00:22:55.499 --> 00:22:57.834
It becomes bigger
            than the song

486
00:22:57.834 --> 00:22:59.961
and sometimes bigger
          than the artist.

487
00:22:59.961 --> 00:23:02.672
And that's definitely
     something to watch out for.

488
00:23:02.672 --> 00:23:05.217
especially on
          your first album.

489
00:23:09.805 --> 00:23:11.431
-They put
       "Leaving Las Vegas" out

490
00:23:11.431 --> 00:23:13.016
and it started
          to have traction.

491
00:23:13.016 --> 00:23:16.061
We started to get some TV.
     and I got David Letterman.

492
00:23:16.061 --> 00:23:19.272
-Now. this right here. kids.
      is her debut CD entitled

493
00:23:19.272 --> 00:23:20.690
"Tuesday Night Music Club."

494
00:23:20.690 --> 00:23:23.527
Making her first appearance
              with us.

495
00:23:23.527 --> 00:23:24.694
here's Sheryl Crow.

496
00:23:24.694 --> 00:23:26.446
Sheryl. come on out.

497
00:23:35.872 --> 00:23:38.792
Life springs eternal

498
00:23:38.792 --> 00:23:42.629
On a gaudy neon street

499
00:23:42.629 --> 00:23:45.173
Not that I care at all

500
00:23:47.843 --> 00:23:48.969
Now I'm...

501
00:23:48.969 --> 00:23:50.512
You know. you grow up
          and you watch TV.

502
00:23:50.512 --> 00:23:51.888
and you see Ed Sullivan
       and you see Dick Clark

503
00:23:51.888 --> 00:23:53.723
and he's interviewing people
             and stuff.

504
00:23:53.723 --> 00:23:55.100
And that's TV. you know.

505
00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:57.269
and then all of a sudden
            you're on TV.

506
00:23:57.269 --> 00:24:01.857
I'm leaving Las Vegas

507
00:24:02.899 --> 00:24:05.735
David Letterman. who
     was really the first person

508
00:24:05.735 --> 00:24:07.946
to have me on national TV.

509
00:24:07.946 --> 00:24:10.157
who had kind of discovered
        the record on his own

510
00:24:10.157 --> 00:24:12.200
driving back and forth to
      his house in Connecticut.

511
00:24:12.200 --> 00:24:13.910
said. you know.
     "Come over and talk to me."

512
00:24:13.910 --> 00:24:16.746
and. you know.
       it was Dave Letterman.

513
00:24:16.746 --> 00:24:19.416
-Nice to see you.
       Thanks for being here.

514
00:24:19.416 --> 00:24:21.251
-Thank you.
         -Have a seat there.

515
00:24:22.544 --> 00:24:24.880
The crowd goes crazy.
               -Whaa!

516
00:24:24.880 --> 00:24:26.590
He said.
       "So what is this song?

517
00:24:26.590 --> 00:24:28.049
Is this thing
         autobiographical?"

518
00:24:28.049 --> 00:24:30.802
And I'm so nervous. I'm like.
      "Well. I mean. kind of."

519
00:24:30.802 --> 00:24:32.679
-I'm guessing -- and I think
    I know the answer to this --

520
00:24:32.679 --> 00:24:34.973
that song in some way
      must be autobiographical.

521
00:24:34.973 --> 00:24:36.933
Is that correct?
              -Uh. yes.

522
00:24:36.933 --> 00:24:40.312
-Which is a stupid question
         for a guy like him.

523
00:24:40.312 --> 00:24:44.733
It's like. it's a   character
        sung by Sheryl Crow.

524
00:24:44.733 --> 00:24:47.569
This is a little complicated
         to describe. right?

525
00:24:47.569 --> 00:24:50.155
So she said. "Yeah."

526
00:24:51.698 --> 00:24:53.575
Well. you know...

527
00:24:53.575 --> 00:24:55.452
-I've never lived there.
 -You never lived in Las Vegas.

528
00:24:55.452 --> 00:24:56.870
-No. I haven't.
         -You worked there?

529
00:24:56.870 --> 00:24:58.497
-Haven't really worked there
               either.

530
00:24:58.497 --> 00:24:59.664
-Have you ever been there?

531
00:24:59.664 --> 00:25:00.957
-Yes. I've lost
        a lot of money there.

532
00:25:00.957 --> 00:25:02.626
-Could you find it on a map?
                -Yes.

533
00:25:02.626 --> 00:25:05.212
I wasn't prepared for
          how overwhelming

534
00:25:05.212 --> 00:25:08.840
it would feel to have somebody
      that I had watched on TV

535
00:25:08.840 --> 00:25:10.217
ask me questions.

536
00:25:10.217 --> 00:25:12.093
Originally. the song was very
   metaphorical for Los Angeles.

537
00:25:12.093 --> 00:25:14.137
that people move there
       with these great dreams

538
00:25:14.137 --> 00:25:15.847
and they wind up
      being very disillusioned.

539
00:25:15.847 --> 00:25:19.643
And so that's what Las Vegas
         seems to exemplify.

540
00:25:19.643 --> 00:25:20.936
-Then why didn't you
            call the song

541
00:25:20.936 --> 00:25:22.020
"I'm Leaving Los Angeles"?

542
00:25:22.020 --> 00:25:24.314
In fact.
    every major American city --

543
00:25:24.314 --> 00:25:26.733
"I'm Leaving Minneapolis."

544
00:25:26.733 --> 00:25:28.026
"I'm Leaving Milwaukee."

545
00:25:28.026 --> 00:25:29.903
-Milwaukee's a good one. yeah.

546
00:25:29.903 --> 00:25:32.489
"I'm Leaving New York"...
              shortly.

547
00:25:32.489 --> 00:25:33.615
-No.

548
00:25:35.158 --> 00:25:37.827
-Yes. if I could go back
          and do it again.

549
00:25:37.827 --> 00:25:39.246
certainly I would feel my feet

550
00:25:39.246 --> 00:25:41.706
and I would try to put myself
     in my body and I would say.

551
00:25:41.706 --> 00:25:43.667
"You know. what a great
     experience being in a room

552
00:25:43.667 --> 00:25:45.919
with all these incredible.
         intellectual people

553
00:25:45.919 --> 00:25:47.671
and being able
          to jam a song out

554
00:25:47.671 --> 00:25:49.089
and put together lyrics
             together."

555
00:25:49.089 --> 00:25:52.759
And. you know. I could have
     told that story. you know.

556
00:25:52.759 --> 00:25:55.220
but I couldn't think.

557
00:25:55.220 --> 00:25:59.099
-The drama that followed --
         it was a shit show.

558
00:25:59.099 --> 00:26:03.645
-And I came home the next day
      to just a massive blow-up

559
00:26:03.645 --> 00:26:05.939
of the guys in the group
               saying.

560
00:26:05.939 --> 00:26:07.816
"She's taken
       totally credit for it."

561
00:26:07.816 --> 00:26:10.068
And then come to find out
     that there had been a book

562
00:26:10.068 --> 00:26:11.695
called "Leaving Las Vegas."

563
00:26:11.695 --> 00:26:15.031
And the title
        was brought in to us

564
00:26:15.031 --> 00:26:17.993
by one of the guys in
   the Tuesday Night Music Club.

565
00:26:17.993 --> 00:26:20.787
And he had said
     we had promised the writer.

566
00:26:20.787 --> 00:26:22.122
John O'Brien. publishing.

567
00:26:22.122 --> 00:26:24.165
and that
      I was fully aware of it.

568
00:26:24.165 --> 00:26:28.461
And after David Letterman.
   the author committed suicide.

569
00:26:30.505 --> 00:26:32.424
And...

570
00:26:34.884 --> 00:26:36.886
I just...

571
00:26:36.886 --> 00:26:39.139
I mean.
      I just went into a hole.

572
00:26:39.139 --> 00:26:41.975
I -- I just went into a hole.

573
00:26:42.726 --> 00:26:46.104
-The press unfairly cast her
           as the bad guy.

574
00:26:46.104 --> 00:26:49.441
and she carried that weight
          for a long time.

575
00:26:51.943 --> 00:26:53.862
-It's that good-girl thing
       where you're just like.

576
00:26:53.862 --> 00:26:55.238
"I would never hurt anybody.

577
00:26:55.238 --> 00:26:56.865
I would never want
        anybody to be hurt."

578
00:26:56.865 --> 00:26:59.075
And then
     it's all of that. you know.

579
00:26:59.075 --> 00:27:02.912
It all ties into...

580
00:27:02.912 --> 00:27:04.706
you know. work hard.
          be a good person.

581
00:27:04.706 --> 00:27:06.958
And then you just --
          all of a sudden.

582
00:27:06.958 --> 00:27:08.585
you just wake up and you're --

583
00:27:08.585 --> 00:27:12.380
wake up and you realize. wow.

584
00:27:12.380 --> 00:27:14.549
What happened? So...

585
00:27:15.800 --> 00:27:19.679
Can we just
     take a break for a second?

586
00:27:23.099 --> 00:27:25.477
Picking up an "L.A. Weekly"
       and seeing an interview

587
00:27:25.477 --> 00:27:28.772
with the person that was in
      Tuesday Night Music Club.

588
00:27:28.772 --> 00:27:31.983
and to read it in print
       and to see the lies --

589
00:27:31.983 --> 00:27:33.902
it changed me.

590
00:27:33.902 --> 00:27:36.112
-I never supported
           that narrative.

591
00:27:36.112 --> 00:27:37.906
The press wants a drama.

592
00:27:37.906 --> 00:27:41.951
-It took that little.
       innocent. young person

593
00:27:41.951 --> 00:27:43.286
that was on David Letterman

594
00:27:43.286 --> 00:27:48.166
and made me not want to be
         accessible anymore.

595
00:27:51.586 --> 00:27:54.464
-And the Best New Artist is...

596
00:27:54.464 --> 00:27:56.132
-Sheryl Crow.

597
00:27:56.132 --> 00:27:58.093
-At that point. there was
       quite a lot of friction

598
00:27:58.093 --> 00:27:59.386
with the
      Tuesday Night Music Club.

599
00:27:59.386 --> 00:28:02.222
And I remember looking out
           and seeing them

600
00:28:02.222 --> 00:28:06.017
and not feeling the happiness
            or the pride.

601
00:28:06.017 --> 00:28:07.227
But nonetheless.
          they were there.

602
00:28:07.227 --> 00:28:09.938
and just how self-conscious
               I felt.

603
00:28:09.938 --> 00:28:11.731
Most importantly. I want
       to thank Bill Bottrell.

604
00:28:11.731 --> 00:28:13.149
who helped me make
            this record.

605
00:28:13.149 --> 00:28:15.235
and all the artists I've been
         very inspired by --

606
00:28:15.235 --> 00:28:17.862
David Baerwald.
 David Ricketts. Kevin Gilbert.

607
00:28:17.862 --> 00:28:19.280
Wyn Cooper. who actually
            came up with

608
00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:20.990
"All I wanna do
         is have some fun."

609
00:28:20.990 --> 00:28:22.867
Most importantly. though.
     I want to thank my manager.

610
00:28:22.867 --> 00:28:25.870
who's a first-time manager
       who's been working for

611
00:28:25.870 --> 00:28:28.206
no money up until now for me.

612
00:28:28.206 --> 00:28:30.083
He's my best friend.
         His name's Scooter.

613
00:28:30.083 --> 00:28:32.127
And he really deserves this.

614
00:28:32.127 --> 00:28:33.753
By the end of the night.

615
00:28:33.753 --> 00:28:35.380
the last award --
       it's the biggest award.

616
00:28:35.380 --> 00:28:37.799
You're up against
         Bruce Springsteen.

617
00:28:37.799 --> 00:28:40.677
I was not thinking
        that I was gonna win.

618
00:28:40.677 --> 00:28:43.805
-And the Record of the Year
                is...

619
00:28:44.848 --> 00:28:47.058
..."All I Wanna Do."
            Sheryl Crow.

620
00:28:48.560 --> 00:28:50.270
- All I wanna do

621
00:28:50.270 --> 00:28:52.856
Bill was very consistent
           with who he was

622
00:28:52.856 --> 00:28:53.857
when we made the record.

623
00:28:53.857 --> 00:28:55.942
We accepted the Grammys
              together

624
00:28:55.942 --> 00:28:57.193
and it was a celebration.

625
00:28:57.193 --> 00:29:01.114
I mean. it really was.
    And that changed everything.

626
00:29:01.948 --> 00:29:04.826
As soon as that record won
         Record of the Year.

627
00:29:04.826 --> 00:29:07.036
Best New Artist.
          Song of the Year.

628
00:29:07.036 --> 00:29:10.290
our record sales doubled.

629
00:29:10.290 --> 00:29:12.709
-Sheryl was working 24/7 --

630
00:29:12.709 --> 00:29:15.670
videos. interviews. concerts.

631
00:29:15.670 --> 00:29:17.088
It was just never-ending.

632
00:29:17.088 --> 00:29:18.840
-The irony of it was. though.

633
00:29:18.840 --> 00:29:20.800
we hadn't seen any money
              from it.

634
00:29:20.800 --> 00:29:24.137
My manager was still
      working out of his closet

635
00:29:24.137 --> 00:29:26.347
across the hall
         from his apartment.

636
00:29:26.347 --> 00:29:28.725
and I was still driving
         an old Volkswagen.

637
00:29:28.725 --> 00:29:31.269
Volkswagen.

638
00:29:31.269 --> 00:29:33.313
-Sheryl and I
      would share a hotel room.

639
00:29:33.313 --> 00:29:35.148
I would get up
       at 00 in the morning.

640
00:29:35.148 --> 00:29:36.357
go down to the lobby.

641
00:29:36.357 --> 00:29:38.860
and have my calling card
         in the phone booth.

642
00:29:38.860 --> 00:29:40.111
And that was that.

643
00:29:40.111 --> 00:29:43.281
And then if. like. I had
     a girlfriend and she'd call

644
00:29:43.281 --> 00:29:45.742
or Sheryl was dating somebody
          and they'd call.

645
00:29:45.742 --> 00:29:47.076
we would kind of
         make believe. like.

646
00:29:47.076 --> 00:29:48.870
"Oh. let me see
           if she's here."

647
00:29:48.870 --> 00:29:53.082
and then count 10 seconds
      and hand the phone over.

648
00:29:53.082 --> 00:29:54.417
-Those were awesome days.

649
00:29:54.417 --> 00:29:56.085
I mean. you know.
         you got off stage.

650
00:29:56.085 --> 00:29:57.170
you hung out with your band.

651
00:29:57.170 --> 00:29:58.421
played music.
          drank some beers.

652
00:29:58.421 --> 00:30:00.381
crawled into bed.
   and woke up the next morning.

653
00:30:00.381 --> 00:30:03.343
did press all day.
          soundcheck. gig.

654
00:30:03.343 --> 00:30:05.929
drink some beers.
 watch a movie. go back to bed.

655
00:30:05.929 --> 00:30:08.139
It was like
      the same thing on repeat.

656
00:30:08.139 --> 00:30:09.557
We finally got a tour bus.

657
00:30:09.557 --> 00:30:12.101
and that was. like.
        the biggest day ever.

658
00:30:12.101 --> 00:30:15.063
Come back. come back.
     This one down here is mine.

659
00:30:15.063 --> 00:30:18.942
So you can see you have
       the necessary tools --

660
00:30:18.942 --> 00:30:22.529
leather hat. Pumas. 

661
00:30:22.529 --> 00:30:25.448
and a curling iron. of course.
          and other things

662
00:30:25.448 --> 00:30:27.742
that we don't have
     to really get into. do we?

663
00:30:27.742 --> 00:30:28.660
Ha. ha!

664
00:30:28.660 --> 00:30:31.996
It was a pink bus and it had
      a tilted champagne glass

665
00:30:31.996 --> 00:30:33.998
with little droplets. and
     whenever people would yell.

666
00:30:33.998 --> 00:30:36.709
"Who's in the tour bus?"
          we'd always yell.

667
00:30:36.709 --> 00:30:38.628
"Dolly Parton!"

668
00:30:40.755 --> 00:30:43.216
I got a dog named Scout.

669
00:30:43.216 --> 00:30:45.552
I adopted him.

670
00:30:45.552 --> 00:30:46.803
It's Scout!

671
00:30:46.803 --> 00:30:48.263
And he went on every tour.

672
00:30:48.263 --> 00:30:53.059
with the exception of
       overseas. for 13 years.

673
00:30:55.687 --> 00:30:57.146
Ah. happiness.

674
00:30:57.146 --> 00:31:00.108
-I remember driving down
     Sunset and seeing her name

675
00:31:00.108 --> 00:31:01.901
on the marquee of the Whiskey.

676
00:31:01.901 --> 00:31:05.321
Like. "Oh. man. she did it!

677
00:31:05.321 --> 00:31:08.783
She did it!
        Wow. this is crazy."

678
00:31:09.117 --> 00:31:13.246
- Ah. yeah. yeah. yeah. run

679
00:31:13.246 --> 00:31:19.544
Run baby. run baby.
           run baby. run

680
00:31:23.506 --> 00:31:29.262
Run baby. run baby.
        run baby. run baby

681
00:31:29.262 --> 00:31:31.890
Run

682
00:31:35.018 --> 00:31:40.899
Run baby. run baby.
        run baby. run baby

683
00:31:40.899 --> 00:31:42.817
Run

684
00:31:44.152 --> 00:31:48.281
Gotta keep on running. run

685
00:31:48.281 --> 00:31:49.282
Run baby

686
00:31:49.282 --> 00:31:50.491
We were in France.

687
00:31:50.491 --> 00:31:52.577
which was where my record
       was doing really well.

688
00:31:52.577 --> 00:31:56.164
00 in the morning.
   I get a call from Mick Jagger

689
00:31:56.164 --> 00:31:57.665
asking me if I would come

690
00:31:57.665 --> 00:32:00.585
and do their pay-per-view
         with them in Miami.

691
00:32:00.585 --> 00:32:02.420
And they were gonna send
           a private jet.

692
00:32:02.420 --> 00:32:04.172
which I'd never seen
           a private jet.

693
00:32:04.172 --> 00:32:06.299
And I got over there.
         and Keith came over

694
00:32:06.299 --> 00:32:09.260
and put his arm around me.
     and. "Hey. little sister."

695
00:32:09.260 --> 00:32:12.305
which he has called me
             ever since.

696
00:32:13.473 --> 00:32:15.350
-I had known something
            about Sheryl.

697
00:32:15.350 --> 00:32:16.643
I had heard her records.

698
00:32:16.643 --> 00:32:20.021
What a great voice. you know.
      really. you know. strong.

699
00:32:20.021 --> 00:32:22.190
-We rehearsed it.
            It went fine.

700
00:32:22.190 --> 00:32:25.818
The next day I got up.
      I threw up all day long.

701
00:32:25.818 --> 00:32:28.488
I was totally terrified.

702
00:32:28.488 --> 00:32:29.864
I get ready. I go over there.

703
00:32:29.864 --> 00:32:32.450
I'm telling Scooter. "I just
     don't think I can do this."

704
00:32:32.450 --> 00:32:33.618
-She's flown a long way
            to get here.

705
00:32:33.618 --> 00:32:35.620
I'm hoping she's got over
            her jet lag.

706
00:32:35.620 --> 00:32:37.956
-And right before
         I was walking out.

707
00:32:37.956 --> 00:32:40.166
as Mick was announcing me.

708
00:32:40.166 --> 00:32:42.335
Bobby Keys handed me
       some tequila and said.

709
00:32:42.335 --> 00:32:45.171
"Take a shot of courage."
         and pushed me out.

710
00:32:45.171 --> 00:32:49.092
-I wish her luck.
     Beautiful Miss Sheryl Crow.

711
00:32:58.518 --> 00:33:01.813
I got nasty habits

712
00:33:01.813 --> 00:33:04.065
I take tea at three

713
00:33:04.065 --> 00:33:06.693
With the meat I eat
            for dinner

714
00:33:06.693 --> 00:33:10.154
I must be hung up
            for a week

715
00:33:10.154 --> 00:33:14.659
-She would very well handle
       Mick Jagger. you know.

716
00:33:14.659 --> 00:33:18.371
To me. just standing
        in the back going...

717
00:33:18.371 --> 00:33:20.123
"Wow. this girl's strong.
              you know?

718
00:33:20.123 --> 00:33:23.376
She's not putting up
     with any of his bullshit."

719
00:33:23.584 --> 00:33:27.046
- Don'cha think
      there's a place for us

720
00:33:27.046 --> 00:33:29.132
Right across the street?

721
00:33:29.716 --> 00:33:33.344
Don'cha think
      there's a place for you

722
00:33:33.344 --> 00:33:35.638
In between the sheets?

723
00:33:35.638 --> 00:33:38.266
- Yeah
     -She was very strong girl.

724
00:33:38.266 --> 00:33:40.727
Later on. a very genuine girl.

725
00:33:40.727 --> 00:33:44.272
In a way. very sensitive
      and very sweet. you know.

726
00:33:44.272 --> 00:33:46.315
But there's a lot of tough
              in there.

727
00:33:46.315 --> 00:33:49.360
and. you know.
      which is a good mixture.

728
00:33:51.696 --> 00:33:55.324
-I went home. and Bill and I
      decided we'd get together

729
00:33:55.324 --> 00:33:58.327
and write.
        and we drank martinis

730
00:33:58.327 --> 00:34:02.623
and went out for a great
    dinner and did some writing.

731
00:34:02.623 --> 00:34:07.336
and then we decided
     we would go to New Orleans

732
00:34:07.336 --> 00:34:09.547
to make our record.

733
00:34:10.715 --> 00:34:13.801
The first record had sold like
     five or six million copies.

734
00:34:13.801 --> 00:34:17.555
and we headed down to Kingsway
      with this immense amount

735
00:34:17.555 --> 00:34:19.515
of pressure
      for the sophomore record

736
00:34:19.515 --> 00:34:22.143
to live up to the first
               record.

737
00:34:22.143 --> 00:34:23.394
You know. that word
            "potential."

738
00:34:23.394 --> 00:34:24.604
how it can be so negative.

739
00:34:24.604 --> 00:34:26.355
Like. "You have   such
              potential."

740
00:34:26.355 --> 00:34:28.399
It's almost like. "Man.
     you could really blow it."

741
00:34:28.399 --> 00:34:30.651
What   potential.   you know?

742
00:34:30.651 --> 00:34:33.696
Our first day at Kingsway
         was kind of quirky.

743
00:34:33.696 --> 00:34:37.450
We get there. and this woman
 rolls out from under the board

744
00:34:37.450 --> 00:34:40.369
on. like. an automobile caddy
             on her back

745
00:34:40.369 --> 00:34:42.455
with goggles
        and a soldering iron.

746
00:34:42.455 --> 00:34:44.415
So we thought.
    well. that doesn't bode well

747
00:34:44.415 --> 00:34:46.542
for the beautiful new console.

748
00:34:46.542 --> 00:34:47.668
We're kind of just getting.

749
00:34:47.668 --> 00:34:49.462
you know.
      acclimated to the place.

750
00:34:49.462 --> 00:34:53.257
And as this woman was leaving.
      she kind of scolded Bill

751
00:34:53.257 --> 00:34:55.343
about putting his drink
           on the console.

752
00:34:55.343 --> 00:34:57.220
And so immediately
            it was like.

753
00:34:57.220 --> 00:35:00.223
"Mm. This is a weird way
             to start."

754
00:35:00.223 --> 00:35:03.392
-I do have a very vague memory

755
00:35:03.392 --> 00:35:06.437
of asking whoever it was

756
00:35:06.437 --> 00:35:08.272
that was on the other side
           of the console

757
00:35:08.272 --> 00:35:10.900
to remove their beverage
          from the console

758
00:35:10.900 --> 00:35:13.653
because it's inappropriate.
      and everybody knows that.

759
00:35:13.653 --> 00:35:15.613
-I think we spent the day
              in there

760
00:35:15.613 --> 00:35:16.739
kind of messing around.

761
00:35:16.739 --> 00:35:20.201
and more things didn't work
              than did.

762
00:35:20.201 --> 00:35:22.203
-Daniel Lanois
          built the studio.

763
00:35:22.203 --> 00:35:24.122
I swear he threw
         half of it together

764
00:35:24.122 --> 00:35:25.623
before we got there. you know?

765
00:35:25.623 --> 00:35:27.834
-They think the studio sucks.
         Nothing's working.

766
00:35:27.834 --> 00:35:29.585
The gear won't work
        if you're mad at it.

767
00:35:29.585 --> 00:35:33.047
-We're trying to work.
     and it's Sheryl's got this.

768
00:35:33.047 --> 00:35:34.632
"Yeah. but" attitude.

769
00:35:34.632 --> 00:35:37.885
-We broke and went to dinner
   and once again had some wine.

770
00:35:37.885 --> 00:35:40.930
And the next morning
      I woke up with a headache

771
00:35:40.930 --> 00:35:41.764
and no producer.

772
00:35:41.764 --> 00:35:44.767
-I'm like.
       "I don't belong here."

773
00:35:44.767 --> 00:35:46.894
And I got on a plane
           and came home.

774
00:35:46.894 --> 00:35:52.358
-I was there and had booked
    the studio and was panicked.

775
00:35:52.358 --> 00:35:53.568
I called Scooter.

776
00:35:53.568 --> 00:35:55.528
-Sheryl said. "Bill has left.
             He's done.

777
00:35:55.528 --> 00:35:57.655
He's not -- he's not gonna
        work on the record."

778
00:35:57.655 --> 00:36:00.324
It was a frightening moment
              for her.

779
00:36:00.324 --> 00:36:01.659
And he said.
      "Why don't you call Jeff

780
00:36:01.659 --> 00:36:04.328
and see if he's interested
          in coming down."

781
00:36:04.328 --> 00:36:05.580
The guitar player Jeff Trott.

782
00:36:05.580 --> 00:36:07.331
I didn't really
           know very well.

783
00:36:07.331 --> 00:36:11.085
He played a little like
            an '80s take

784
00:36:11.085 --> 00:36:13.546
on Keith Richards.
            if you will.

785
00:36:14.672 --> 00:36:19.010
-I get this call. like. really
     super early in the morning.

